time management. I have to balance my time between sports (I’m a track and soccer player), my orchestra, my business, and schoolwork. I’m also a member of two honor societies, Rho Kappa (social studies) and Mu Alpha Theta (mathematics). When I manage my time, I rather try to prioritize learning. I can easily take a 3 hour nap or watch tv for hours on end, but I know that watching tv won’t help me one bit when I’m applying to college (regardless of what you may think about such rankings). I know that the more time I spend watching tv, the less I’m able to spend effectively learning about the world. The fact that education is so much more accessible than ever before is enormously exciting in that it EFFICIENTLY provides knowledge and presents information. This is radically different from a pre-Internet age and even only a few years ago where you would have to have a college degree for access to the alphabet of life. We are experiencing a renaissance of sorts where internet information can be accessible to all; one that is much more egalitarian in nature at the cost of certain realities of our inefficient system (the profit-aligned, normalization procedures such as standardized testing and higher educational institution hierarchies) that provides this information; we can glean the bias and learn about how people have interpreted things, we can read the language that our professors behind their own glasses and their own counteracted experiences.
